text: International Microbiology https://doi.org/10.1007/s10123-019-00071-7 Characterisation of Two Polyketides from Streptomyces sp. SKH1-2 Isolated from Roots of Musa (ABB) cv. ‘Kluai Sao Kratuep Ho’ Nattakorn Kuncharoen 1 & Wataru Fukasawa 2,3 & Masato Iwatsuki 2,3 & Mihoko Mori 2,3 & Kazuro Shiomi 2,3 & Somboon Tanasupawat 1 Received: 7 January 2019 / Revised: 7 February 2019 / Accepted: 5 March 2019 # Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2019 Abstract An endophytic actinomycete strain SKH1-2 isolated from Musa (ABB) cv. ‘Kluai Sao Kratuep Ho’ collected in Suphan Buri province (14° 54′ 22.5″ N/100° 04′ 50″ E), Thailand, was identified as Streptomyces pseudovenezuelae based on phenotypic and chemotaxonomic characteristics, and 16S rRNA sequence analyses. A chemical investigation led to the isolation of two poly- ketide molecules from the n-butanol crude extract of the strain SKH1-2 culture broth. The compounds were purified using various chromatographic techniques and identified using spectroscopic methods compared with earlier published data. Compound 1, chartreusin, is known as an anti-Gram (+) bacterial compound and was active against Bacillus subtilis ATCC 6633, Kocuria rhizophila ATCC 9341 and Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 6538p with MIC values of 3.1, 1.6 and 12.5 μg/mL, respectively. Compound 2, lumichrome, did not show activity against all tested microbes. To our knowledge, this is the first report of chartreusin and lumichrome isolated from S. pseudovenezuelae. Taken together, it could be proved that Thai plant species are valuable reservoirs of interesting endophytic actinomycetes producing several interesting biologically active compounds.

Keywords Antimicrobial activity . Endophytic actinomycetes . Streptomyces . Polyketides Plant endosphere is a myriad of micro-ecosystems where differ- ent niches can be resided by a lot of different microbes, and it provides a great and trustworthy source of actinomycetes (El- Shatoury et al. 2013). Endophytic actinomycetes have been re- vealed as an extraordinary source of bioactive secondary metab- olites. They are widely distributed in various types of plants: medicinal plants, crops, woody plants, mangrove plants, and in- digenous plants (Supong et al. 2016). Plant-derived actinomy- cetes were really found to fall within a narrow genera distribution: * Somboon Tanasupawat Somboon.T@chula.ac.th 1 Department of Biochemistry and Microbiology, Faculty of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Chulalongkorn University, Bangkok 10330, Thailand 2 Graduate School of Infection Control Sciences, Kitasato University, 3 Kitasato Institute for Life Sciences, Kitasato University, Minato-ku, Minato-ku, Tokyo 108-8641, Japan

Streptomyces represented a predominant genus, and Micromonospora, Microbispora, Nocardia, Nocardioides, Pseudonocardia and Streptosporangium were also considered as common genera (Qin et al. 2009). Over the last decade, nu- merous secondary metabolites discovered from endophytic acti- nomycetes have been reported, for instance, polyketides (Inahashi et al. 2011), macrolides (Inahashi et al. 2015) and ter- penes (Ding et al. 2015). These metabolites showed various bio- logical activities such as antibacterial, antifungal, anti-phytopath- ogens, immunosuppressant and anticancer (Strobel et al. 2004). Although various genera of actinomycetes have been isolated from plant endosphere, most of the Streptomyces strains have been remarkably produced numerous bioactive compounds, for example, bacaryolanes A-C (Ding et al. 2015), kandenols A-E (Ding et al. 2012) and bafilomycins (Yu et al. 2011). Thus, endophytic actinomycetes are promising as a source for discov- ery of novel bioactive compounds. The endophytic Streptomyces sp. SKH1-2 isolated from Musa (ABB) cv. ‘Kluai Sao Kratuep Ho’ in Thailand was cho- sen from antimicrobial activity screening by disk diffusion meth- od (Mearns-Spragg et al. 1998) because its crude extract (17 μg/ disk) showed significantly active against B. subtilis ATCC 6633, K. rhizophila ATCC 9341 and S. aureus ATCC 6538p with the inhibition zones of 18.4, 21.1 and 18.1 mm, respectively. Therefore, the present study aimed to identify the isolate SKH1-2 according to the polyphasic taxonomy. Moreover, the isolation, purification, structure elucidation and biological eval- uation of the secondary metabolites are also reported. Isolation of Endophytic Actinomycete Strain SKH1-2

The endophytic actinomycete strain SKH1-2, which exhibited a high antimicrobial activity, was isolated from roots of Musa (ABB) cv. ‘Kluai Sao Kratuep Ho’ collected in Suphan Buri province (14° 54′ 22.5″ N/100° 04′ 50″ E), Thailand, from June to August 2015. The root samples were prepared according to the method as described previously (Kuncharoen et al. 2018). An aliquot (0.1 mL) of each sample was spread onto starch casein (Küster and Williams 1964) gellan gum agar medium supple- mented with 25 μg nalidixic acid per millilitre and 50 μg cyclo- heximide per millilitre. Colonies of the isolate SKH1-2 were purified on ISP 2 agar medium (Shirling and Gottlieb 1966). The pure culture was maintained in 15% (v/v) glycerol solution at − 80 °C and lyophilised for long-term preservation. Identification of Strain SKH1-2

Strain SKH1-2 was identified based on the polyphasic taxonom- ic approach. Cultural characteristics of the strain SKH1-2 were determined on ISP 2 agar according to the standard method (Shirling and Gottlieb 1966). The names and designations of the colony and diffusible pigment colours were determined by using the ISCC-NBS colour system (Kelly 1964). The tempera- ture range (20–55 °C), pH range (4–10) and NaCl (1–9%, w/v) tolerance for growth were evaluated on ISP 2 agar. The utilisation of various carbohydrates as sole carbon sources was assessed using ISP 9 (Nihon Pharmaceutical) as the basal medi- um according to the standard method (Shirling and Gottlieb 1966). Starch hydrolysis, nitrate reduction, gelatin liquefaction, milk coagulation and peptonisation and acid production were tested according to the standard procedures (Arai 1975; Gordon et al. 1974). The isomers of cell-wall diaminopimelic acid (A2pm) were determined by using thin-layer chromatogra- phy (TLC) as described earlier (Staneck and Roberts 1974). Chromosomal DNA of the strain SKH1-2 was prepared by the modified method as previously described (Kudo et al. 1998). The 16S rRNA gene sequence of the isolate was amplified using the primers 20F (5′-GAGTTTGATCCTGGCTCAG-3′, positions 9– 27) and 1500R (5′-GTTACCTTGTTACGACTT-3′, positions 1509–1492) (Suriyachadkun et al. 2009). The amplifications were carried out with an initial incubation of 1 min at 95 °C, followed by 30 cycles of 1 min at 95 °C, 1 min at 50 °C,

1.5 min at 72 °C, followed by 2 min final extension at 72 °C. The PCR products were purified and sequenced on a DNA se- quencer (Macrogen, Korea) using universal primers (Lane 1991). Phylogenetic neighbours and calculation of pairwise 16S rRNA gene sequence similarities were accomplished via EzBiocloud server (Yoon et al. 2017). A phylogenetic distance matrix was calculated with the Kimura-2-parameter model (Kimura 1980), and tree topology was inferred by using the neighbour-joining method (Saitou and Nei 1987) which were constructed using MEGA 7.0 programme (Kumar et al. 2016). The bootstrap values were calculated based on 1000 replications (Felsenstein 1985). Production and Isolation of Secondary Metabolites from the Isolate SKH1-2

An endophytic actinomycete strain SKH1-2 was grown and maintained on ISP 2 agar slant. A loopful of cells of strain SKH1-2 was inoculated into a test tube containing 10 mL of the seed medium (2.4% starch, 0.1% glucose, 0.3% peptone, 0.3% meat extract, 0.5% yeast extract and 0.3% CaCO3, pH 7.0). The tubes were cultivated on a rotary shaker (200 rpm) at 28 °C for 4 days. Afterwards, a 1 mL portion of the first seed culture was transferred into a 500-mL Erlenmeyer flask containing 100 mL of the seed medium and incubated at the same condition as described above. For production, a 1 mL portion of the second inoculum was transferred to 500-mL Erlenmeyer flasks (total 60 flasks), each containing 100 mL of the medium 51 (0.5% glucose, 0.5% corn steep powder, 1% oat meal, 1% defatted cotton seed powder, 0.5% K2HPO4, 0.5% MgSO4·7H2O and 1 mL/L of trace metal solution, pH 7.0), at 28 °C, 200 rpm for 7 days. Trace metal solution contained each 1.0 g/L of FeSO4·7H2O, MnCl2·4H2O, ZnSO4·7H2O, CuSO4· 5H2O and CoCl2·6H2O. The production culture was carried out on rotary shakers (200 rpm) for 6 days at 28 °C.

The procedure for isolation of compounds 1 and 2 is summarised in Fig. 1. The 6-day culture broth was firstly extracted with an equivalent volume of 95% (v/v) ethanol and further extracted twice with an equal volume of n-butanol and then evaporated to dryness. The n-butanol crude extract (3.17 g) was firstly separated through a silica gel open-column chromatography eluting with a gradient system of 0–100% CHCl3:CH3OH to yield 7 fractions. The active fraction, CHCl3:CH3OH (9:1) was purified continuously using octadecylsilyl silica gel (ODS) open-column chromatography and eluted with 10–50% of CH3CN in H2O. Obtained 40% and 50% CH3CN fractions were concentrated in vacuo and dryness to furnish pure 1 (71.3 mg and 4.9 mg, respectively; 12.5 mg/L). The 20% CH3CN fraction was further purified by preparative HPLC performing on CAPCELL PAK UG-120 column (Osaka soda Co., 20 mm ϕ × 250 mm) and eluted with an isocratic system of 20% CH3CN in H2O at a flow rate of 7 min/mL to afford pure 2 (20.0 mg; 3.3 mg/L). Chemical shifts were expressed in ppm and were referenced to DMSO-d6 and pyridine-d5 for 1 and 2, respectively, in the 1H NMR and the 13C NMR spectra. ESI-MS spectra were determined on a QSTAR Elite Hybrid MS/MS spec- trometer (AB Sciex Co., MA, USA). Other cultural characteristics of the isolate SKH1-2 were given in Table 1. The growth of isolate SKH1-2 was observed from pH 6.0 to 8.0 with an optimum at 7.0. The isolate grew in a temperature range from 20 to 37 °C (opti- mum at 30 °C) and grew on the agar medium with up to 6% (w/v) NaCl. Additional physiological and biochemical results of isolate SKH1-2 are presented in Table 2. The nearest complete 16S rRNA gene sequence of strain SKH1-2 (1441 nt), deposited in the DDBJ with an accession number of LC425851 revealed that the isolate was identical to Streptomyces pseudovenezuelae DSM40212T with the highest 16S rRNA sequence similarity of 99.37%. A neighbour- joining phylogenetic analysis of 16S rRNA gene sequences (Fig. 2) also emphasised that the strain formed a cluster with S. pseudovenezuelae DSM 40212T and S. cyaneus NRRL B-2296T. After extraction and evaporation, the n-butanol crude extract of the whole fermented broth of the strain SKH1-2 was fractionated using silica gel and ODS open-column chromatography and further purified by preparative HPLC to effort the two com- pounds 1–2. Chemical structures of the compounds (Fig. 3) were determined using NMR, ESI-MS and UV spectroscopy, integrat- ed with the reference data of the previous studies. Compound 1 was obtained as greenish-yellow solid. ESI- MS analyses indicated a molecular formula of 1 was C32H32O14 (m/z found 663.1740 [M + Na] +, calcd 640.1740). Spectroscopic information involving 1H NMR and 13C NMR spectral data (Table 3) led to the chemical structure of com- pound 1. Based on its spectral data, this compound was identi- fied to be chartreusin (Fig. 3) which firstly isolated from Streptomyces chartreusis AS 4.1639 (Leach et al. 1953). Compound 2 was obtained as yellow solid. 1H NMR and 13C NMR spectral information (Table 3) was identical to pub- lished data for lumichrome (Tsukamoto et al. 1999). The mo- lecular formula of C12H10N4O2 was asserted by ESI-MS anal- ysis, giving the mass ion at m/z found 265.0759 [M + Na]+, calcd 242.0759 with its structure as shown in Fig. 3. Bar, 0.005 substitutions per nucleotide position Antibacterial Activity of Compounds 1 and 2

The antimicrobial activity of compounds 1 and 2 was deter- mined as shown in Table 4. Compound (2) was inactive against the tested organisms, whereas compound (1) showed strong antibacterial activity against B. subtilis ATCC 6633, K. rhizophila ATCC 9341 and S. aureus ATCC 6538p with MIC values of 3.1, 1.6 and 12.5 μg/mL, respectively. Compound 1 exhibited weak antimicrobial activity against E. coli NIHJ and P. aeruginosa ATCC 27853 (MIC values > 50 μg/mL), and inactive against X. campestris pv. oryzae KB88. In the present study, we identified the endophytic Streptomyces sp. SKH1-2 isolated from surface-sterilised root tissues of healthy Musa (ABB) cv. ‘Kluai Sao Kratuep Ho’ in Thailand. Furthermore, the isolation and identification of its secondary metabolites were also described. According to the phylogeny (Fig. 2), the strain SKH1-2 shared a clade with Streptomyces pseudovenezuelae DSM 40212 T and (KQ948892) (AB045877) (AB915216) (HQ267987) Fig. 3 Chemical structure of the isolated compounds (1) chartreusin and (2) lumichrome S. cyaneus NRRL B-2296T, and it should be identified as S. pseudovenezuelae because the 16S rRNA gene sequence similarity of the isolate SKH1-2 was higher than the threshold range of 98.7–99% which is the point for delineation of novel species (Stackebrandt and Ebers 2006). In addition, the phenotypic characteristics of the isolate SKH1-2 were likely to S. pseudovenezuelae (Pridham 1970). Several studies reported that S. pseudovenezuelae AM-2947 produced setomimycin which was active inhibited Gram-positive bacteria including mycobacteria (Omura et al. 1978) and C29H32N2O7 was an in- hibitor of sodium-potassium ATPase (Makoto et al. 1982). Thus, this is the first report of two bioactive compounds, chartreusin a n d l u m i c h r o m e , p r o d u c e d b y t h e e n d o p h y t i c S. pseudovenezuelae SKH1-2.

The endophytic Streptomyces sp. SKH1-2 produced two major secondary metabolites. Compound 1 exhibited strong antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive bacteria with low MIC values and was characterised as chartreusin. Chartreusin (1) was firstly produced by Streptomyces chartreusis (Leach et al. 1953). It showed strongly suppressed the growth of Gram-positive bacteria with low MIC values, but weakly inhibited the growth of Gram-negative bacteria (MIC > 30 μg/mL) (Aoyama et al. 1992). Compound 2 coincided as lumichrome which is a major photodegradation product of riboflavin in neutral or acidic con- ditions. Lumichrome (2) is found in plants and marine animals such as Halocynthia roretzi (Tsukamoto et al. 1999); addition- ally, 2 is also produced by microorganisms Devosia riboflavina, Pseudomonas sp., Microbacterium sp., Streptomyces sp. and Micromonospora sp. (Yamamoto and Asano 2015). Our find- ings were in line with previous studies which reported that 2 has no activity against bacteria and fungi (Shi et al. 2015). Nonetheless, other studies revealed that lumichrome has affect- ed the plant’s growth by increasing cell differentiation and ex- pansion with a consequential increase in biomass (Pholo et al. 2018), enhanced the osteoblast differentiation at early stage and reduced bone loss by inhibiting osteoclastogenesis in patients who suffered with osteolytic diseases (Liu et al. 2018). Lumichrome was a major derivative of riboflavin which may inhibit the growth of tumour cells in animals (Rivlin 1973); consequently, it was interesting for the future study.

To our knowledge, the endophytic strain SKH1-2 identified as S. pseudovenezuelae produced two secondary metabolites which were isolated and purified from its fermented broth. The compound 1, chartreusin, exhibited strong antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacteria such as B. subtilis ATCC 6633, K. rhizophila ATCC 9341 and S. aureus ATCC 6538p, but weakly against Gram-negative bacteria. The com- pound 2, lumichrome, did not show any antimicrobial activity, yet it was a predominant derivative of riboflavin. This ribofla- vin can be used to inhibit cancer cells; thus, the compound 2 could be further studied and considered promising as an anti- cancer agent in the future. Our study suggested that S. pseudovenezuelae SKH1-2 could be a potential bioactive producer. Acknowledgements We faithfully thank Dr. A. Matsumoto, Dr. K. Nonaka, Dr. Y. Asami and Mr. M.
